    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Civil Rights Movement was a massive success in ending legal segregation and securing voting rights, but many historians argue it was incomplete because it failed to dismantle systemic racism or achieve universal voting rights for all groups. While some critics claim the movement's focus on nonviolence slowed progress, others argue that the legislative wins were surface-level changes that didn't address the core issues of economic inequality and police brutality. Ultimately, the debate centers on whether the movement achieved its primary goals or if it left deep-seated injustices unresolved.",
